<p><strong><u>Considerations</u></strong></p>
<ul>
<li>This priming sugar calculator helps a home brewer determine how much of=
 a particular type of priming sugar to use for proper carbonation. For the =
most accurate estimation, it is important to account for how much CO2 is al=
ready dissolved in the beer immediately after fermentation. A freshly ferme=
nted beer will contain some dissolved CO2 as a result of fermentation. This=
 priming calculator estimates this dissolved CO2 based upon the beer=E2=80=
=99s temperature. The amount of this naturally dissolved CO2 is temperature=
 dependent, typically based upon the beer=E2=80=99s fermentation temperatur=
e. If the beer=E2=80=99s temperature rises after fermentation is complete, =
then some of this natural carbonation will be lost, because the CO2=E2=80=
=99s solubility in the beer will decrease with rising temperature. Thus, fo=
r the temperature input, enter the <u>highest temperature</u> the beer expe=
rienced after fermentation completely ended.</li>
<li>For home beer brewers, how important is it to brew a specific beer styl=
e to the historically accepted carbonation values as listed in the above dr=
op down menu? This is just a matter of personal preference. Sometimes it's =
fun to attempt to brew a beer to stylistic authenticity. If you are enterin=
g a home brew contest, then paying attention to carbonation levels can be b=
eneficial. On the other hand, sometimes it's just easier to use the 5 oz of=
 priming sugar included with the recipe and call it a day.</li>
<li>Volumes of CO2 refers to the amount of CO=E2=82=82 gas dissolved in bee=
r. &nbsp;Carbonation is typically measured in volumes=E2=80=94a unit that r=
epresents the volume of CO=E2=82=82 relative to the volume of beer. For exa=
mple, 2.4 volumes means there are 2.4 liters of CO=E2=82=82 dissolved in 1 =
liter of beer at atmospheric pressure and 32=C2=B0 F temperature.</li>
<li>If a fermented beer sits in fermenter with an airlock for a long time, =
some of this natural CO2 will be lost due to simple gas diffusion. Gas alwa=
ys diffuses from a higher concentration to a lower concentration.</li>
<li>Whenever a beer is siphoned or racked from one vessel to another, some =
of this naturally occurring CO2 will be lost due to the physical agitation =
of the beer.</li>
<li>We recommend measuring your chosen priming sugar by weight. This primin=
g sugar calculator lists priming sugars by weight, not volume. Volume is no=
t a reliable measurement, because the density of sugars can differ for many=
 reasons.</li>
<li>When carbonating home brewed beer by priming glass bottles, a best prac=
tice method is to check the bottles for developing carbonation every few da=
ys. This involves opening the beer, pouring it into a glass and evaluating =
the carbonation level. Of course, you get to drink the beer, too!&nbsp; If,=
 on the following days the beer is developing too much carbonation, then yo=
u can prevent any risk of exploding bottles by refrigerating all unopened b=
ottles. The cold refrigerator temperatures will force the yeast into dorman=
cy.</li>
<li>
<span style=3D"text-decoration: underline;">Disclaimer</span>: Always exerc=
ise caution when priming bottles of beer. Do no over prime beer, which can =
result in exploding bottles and personal injury. This Brewer's Priming Calc=
ulator is for estimation purposes only. Because carbonation is a function o=
f many variables, some of which are beyond the control of home brewers, we =
cannot guarantee accuracy provided by this calculator.</li>
</ul>
